metadata.name: dreams #114
metadata.description:
As in a dream, this representation flows, changes direction and evolves.
Each piece represents one different dream. Calm down, nightmares, crossroads, triumphs, longings, forgotten memories, hopes, disappointments... Some have two faces, one light and one dark where sleep flows. Others have a central theme from where our dream is born or dies, in hope or in despair. Others, just flow.

--
Zoom out browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas

Created with p5.js
Diego Pintos, Aug 2022.

metadata.name: EYES #46
metadata.description:
The beauty and soul of eyes have always fascinated me. There are billions of eyes in the world, all with different colors, textures and shapes and each one is still unique. With this project, I wanted to capture that natural beauty of the eyes, but also give them my unique colorful style.

Zombie and Cat eyes are more rare. Who will collect the Zombie Cat eye?

----

Created with the help of amazing cables.gl. For optimization purposes, in order to make the project load properly on fxhash, I had to use 2 textures for the eye pupil shapes instead of procedurally generating them. There is also hdr map loaded for the reflections.  

Press E to download the generated image.

----

All who collected NEBULAE were added to the reserve list. <3

metadata.name: Junkspace #32
metadata.description:
You never notice, it is passthrough. It is familiar but unfamiliar. It is everywhere and nowhere at the same time. It can contain anything, but it doesn't. Being here is lonely, even surrounded. It is the debris of modern architecture. It is the uncanny valley of the places. It is the Junkspace.

Junkspace is an algorithm inspired by the well-known namesake article of Rem Koolhaas (October, Vol. 100, Obsolescence. (Spring, 2002), pp. 175-190). The work is a generative approach to visualize it in the plan view. There are several paper types, partitions, floorings, and color palettes to achieve the residue of modernization.

This work exists thanks to the p5js library. To give some back to the community, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.

Press "s" to save the image.

metadata.name: Alleles #43
metadata.description:
An allele, short for 'allelomorph', is an alternative version of a specific gene.

This collection (which is in no way scientifically accurate), was born out of an exercise in simplicity. Outputs are made up of arrangements of squares in various compositions, yet within that we are free to imagine what they could mean. For some, the resulting shapes might represent DNA strands or atoms. Others might see cells or the building blocks of the hereditary instructions that shape us as individuals. 

A generative genetic report accompanies each output to spark the imagination and attempt to attach further meaning to each composition. Some gene sequences carry mutations, however not all mutations are visually apparent. Please refer to the fxhash features to view the reports accordingly.

Texture is used subtly, so for maximum enjoyment it is recommended that you save and view your outputs at full size in order to best enjoy the details.

Press 'S' to save a 2400 x 3396 px PNG file.

attributes.name: Genetic Profile
attributes.value: Exploration of the extracted genetic profile suggests subject may be succeptible to frequent occurences of disagreeableness and laughter during inappropriate moments, yet also displays the potential for exceptional interpersonal connection and non-linear thinking. Maximum potential hereditary height (excluding nutritional and environmental factors) is estimated at 187-195cm. Projected natural lifespan estimated at 87-87 years.

metadata.name: Zephyr #127
metadata.description:
The name Zephyr traces back to Zephyrus, the Greek god of the west wind, and refers to any light breeze. The flowing particles get pushed around by a zephyr, creating interesting and organic patterns.

Live Mode Controls:

- Default is 2000x2000 pixel canvas. Press “1” for 1000x1000px canvas, “3” for 3000x3000px, “4” for 4000x4000px
- Press 'p' to save a png of the canvas.

metadata.name: Medusa #41
metadata.description:
“Nunc, o fortissime, fare, precor, Perseu, quanta virtute quibusque artibus abstuleris crinita draconibus ora!” - Ovid, Metamorphoses Book IV 769
"Perseus, I beg you to tell us by what prowess and by what arts you carried off that head with snakes for hair."

Medusa is built in 3D with p5.js using physics of oimo.js (see LICENSE.md). 

For high resolution renderings (4x resolution of current canvas size): Open the artwork in its own browser tab, add the parameter '&highres=4' to the url and reload. e.g. https://gateway.fxhash2.xyz/ipfs/<something>/?fxhash=ooXrQmk42nyJd4HAB63v7jJ9R27DiwcbwDaUEYuX3FvGDzfwNog&highres=4 .

For endless waves: Open the artwork in its own browser tab, add the parameter '&infinity=true' to the url and reload. e.g. https://gateway.fxhash2.xyz/ipfs/<something>/?fxhash=ooXrQmk42nyJd4HAB63v7jJ9R27DiwcbwDaUEYuX3FvGDzfwNog&infinity=true .

For an export as .PNG press 'e'.

I am afraid that's all there is to say.

Stefan Schwaha, @sektionschef, https://digitalitility.com/
